      <div class="article-image"><img alt="Republican presidential candidate Jeb Bush discusses climate change during a June 16 campaign town hall in Derry, N.H." src="/web/20170227043512im_/http://www.ncregister.com/images/uploads/Jeb_Bush_climate_change_screenshot.jpg"></div>
    <div class="article-image-caption">Republican presidential candidate Jeb Bush discusses climate change during a June 16 campaign town hall in Derry, N.H. (YouTube/CNN)</div>
    <div class="article-section">
          &nbsp;|&nbsp; Jun. 26, 2015
  </div>
  <div class="article-title">Political Role Reversal: Democrats Praise Encyclical, While GOP Remains Cautious</div>
      <div class="article-subhead"><i>Laudato Si</i> is getting a very different partisan reception from U.S. politicians, compared to previous papal pronouncements that addressed marriage and the sanctity of human life.</div>
    <div class="article-author">    BRIAN FRAGA  </div>
    <div class="article-body"><p>WASHINGTON &mdash; Leading Democrats who are otherwise at odds with the Church&rsquo;s moral teachings have praised Pope Francis for addressing climate change in <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://w2.vatican.va/content/francesco/en/encyclicals/documents/papa-francesco_20150524_enciclica-laudato-si.html" style="line-height: 1.6em;"><em>Laudato Si</em></a> (The Care for Our Common Home), the Pope&rsquo;s encyclical on ecology.</p>

<p>But while President Barack Obama, Hillary Clinton and Sen. Bernie Sanders enthusiastically hailed <em>Laudato Si</em>, Republican congressional leaders and presidential candidates have either downplayed the encyclical&rsquo;s authority or tried to avoid directly commenting on it.</p>

<p>Jesuit Father James Bretzke, a moral theology professor at Boston College, told the Register that both sides are being disingenuous. He accused Democrats and Republicans of &ldquo;cherry-picking&rdquo; parts of the encyclical instead of engaging it directly.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I think it shows that both the Republicans and the Democrats &hellip; like to use religious authority and, in this case, the Pope to support positions they have arrived at independently,&rdquo; Father Bretzke told the Register.</p>

<p>Said Father Bretzke, &ldquo;There is a certain insincerity, a hypocrisy I think, on both sides.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The opposing reactions are striking, since they represent a reversal from previous years, when Republicans could point to the Pope&rsquo;s moral authority for defense of the unborn and traditional marriage, while Democrats could invoke the American conception of separation of church and state whenever those issues arose.</p>

<p>U.S. Sen. Marco Rubio, the junior senator from Florida and a Catholic, is a prospective Republican presidential candidate. Like many of his fellow GOP colleagues, Rubio has tried to walk a fine line on <em>Laudato Si</em>, which the Vatican officially released on June 18.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I have no problem with what the Pope did. He is a moral authority and as a moral authority is reminding us of our obligation to be good caretakers to the planet,&rdquo; Rubio <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2015/06/marco-rubio-no-problem-with-catholic-church-on-climate-change-but-economy-more-important.html">told </a>the <em>Miami Herald</em> before addressing the Miami-Dade County Republican Party.</p>

<p>Rubio, the <em>Herald</em> reported on June 20, said he found it &ldquo;ironic&rdquo; that the same Democrats praising the Pope&rsquo;s stance on climate change ignore his pronouncements on the definition of marriage and sanctity of life.</p>

<p>However, Rubio also questioned the scientific consensus that human activity is largely responsible for climate change and added that his role as a senator is to act for the common good of the environment and the U.S. economy.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Ducking the Question</strong></p>

<p>Rubio engaged the encyclical more directly than most Republicans. U.S. Sen. Ted Cruz, a Texas Republican running for president, who is <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2015/03/24/ted-cruz-says-satellite-data-show-the-globe-isnt-warming-this-satellite-scientist-feels-otherwise/">skeptical </a>of climate change, has not commented on the encyclical. And former U.S. Sen. Rick Santorum, a presidential candidate, and Louisiana Gov. Bobby Jindal, who announced his presidential bid on Wednesday, deflected questions about <em>Laudato Si</em> when they were approached by a Greenpeace activist during the Road to Majority 2015 conference sponsored by the Faith &amp; Freedom Coalition.</p>

<p>During previous interviews when he was asked about Pope Francis weighing in on the climate-change debate, Santorum &mdash; who, like Jindal, is Catholic &mdash; <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2015/06/02/rick-santorum-pope-climat_n_7498768.html">said </a>the Church &ldquo;has gotten it wrong a few times on science&rdquo; and that the Church should &ldquo;stick to&rdquo; its core teachings of theology and morality.</p>

<p>Former Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, who is also Catholic, was asked at the Faith &amp; Freedom Coalition conference if he agreed with the Pope&rsquo;s &ldquo;moral mission on climate change.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&ldquo;He has every right to have a view on it,&rdquo; <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2015/06/22/jeb_bush_i_continue_to_embrace_carbon_emission_reduction.html">said </a>Bush, who days earlier <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/16/us-usa-election-bush-pope-idUSKBN0OW2QQ20150616">had </a>told a New Hampshire audience that he does not get economic policy &ldquo;from my bishops or my cardinals or my pope.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Media &lsquo;Caricature&rsquo;?</strong></p>

<p>Deal Hudson, publisher and editor of <em><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.thechristianreview.com/">The Christian Review</a></em>, told the Register that politicians have been responding to a &ldquo;deliberate caricature&rdquo; of the encyclical created by the national mainstream media to benefit Democrats and make it look like Catholic Republicans are at odds with the Church and the Pope.</p>

<p>&ldquo;There is the encyclical the Pope wrote, and there is the encyclical the media is talking about. The politicians are all talking about what the media is talking about. They&rsquo;re not really talking about the encyclical,&rdquo; said Hudson, who served as director of Catholic outreach for President George W. Bush&rsquo;s 2000 and 2004 presidential campaigns.</p>

<p>Hudson said Democrats and media outlets fail to mention that Pope Francis also writes in the encyclical that the Church is not trying to make a definitive statement about which scientific findings are correct and which are false, but that he is calling for dialogue on an important issue that affects everybody, especially the poor.</p>

<p>In Paragraph 61 of the encyclical, the Pope writes, &ldquo;On many concrete questions, the Church has no reason to offer a definitive opinion; she knows that honest debate must be encouraged among experts, while respecting divergent views. But we need only take a frank look at the facts to see that our common home is falling into serious disrepair.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Said Hudson, &ldquo;Once again they are ignoring the fact that what they&rsquo;re talking about in the encyclical is a prudential matter that is not on the same moral level or status as that of settled moral issues.&rdquo;</p>

<p>And Hudson said Bush and Santorum made the mistake of commenting on the encyclical before its release.</p>

<p>&ldquo;They basically fell into the trap,&rdquo; Hudson said. &ldquo;They should have waited for the encyclical. Then they could have actually praised the encyclical as a whole reaffirmation of the traditional care for God&rsquo;s creation and the need to be a good steward of the resources that God has given to all of us, instead of buying into the mythology that the media has spun.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Other GOP Voices</strong></p>

<p>Meanwhile, Former Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee, a Republican who is also running for president, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.cnn.com/2015/06/18/politics/pope-encyclical-climate-change-catholic-republicans/">told </a>CNN in South Carolina, a key primary state, &ldquo;The last person on Earth I want to try to argue with will be the Pope.&rdquo;</p>

<p>During a press conference, House Speaker John Boehner, who is Catholic,&nbsp;<a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rDTL5LshGww">offered </a>some praise for Pope Francis, while avoiding commenting directly on the encyclical.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Well, one thing we know about this pope is he&rsquo;s not afraid to challenge everyone&rsquo;s thinking of issues frankly, one way or another,&rdquo; said Boehner, adding: &ldquo;And, frankly, I respect his right to speak out on these important issues.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Meanwhile, Sen. Jim Inhofe, R-Okla., an outspoken climate-change skeptic, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://dailycaller.com/2015/06/18/senator-popes-words-will-be-used-to-justify-largest-tax-increase-in-history/">said </a>he disagreed with Francis&rsquo; philosophy on global warming.</p>

<p>&ldquo;I am concerned that his encyclical will be used by global-warming alarmists to advocate for policies that will equate to the largest, most regressive tax increase in our nation&rsquo;s history,&rdquo; Inhofe said.</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Democratic Praise</strong></p>

<p>In sharp contrast, Democrats were eager to issue press releases praising <em>Laudato Si</em>.</p>

<p>President Obama <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2015/06/18/statement-president-pope-francis%E2%80%99s-encyclical">said </a>he welcomed the encyclical and &ldquo;deeply&rdquo; admired the Pope&rsquo;s decision to make the case &mdash; &ldquo;clearly, powerfully and with the full moral authority of his position&rdquo; &mdash; for action on global climate change. The president said he also looked forward to discussing the issue with Pope Francis when the Holy Father visits the White House in September.</p>

<p>House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi, a California Catholic criticized for her positions in favor of abortion rights and same-sex &ldquo;marriage,&rdquo; <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.democraticleader.gov/newsroom/pelosi-remarks-on-his-holiness-pope-francis-encyclical-laudato-si/">said </a>during her weekly press conference that Pope Francis writes &ldquo;with beauty, with clarity and with moral force.&rdquo; She said the encyclical &ldquo;stands as an urgent call for government, industry and the whole community to honor the responsibility to preserve God&rsquo;s creation.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Vice President Joseph Biden and Secretary of State John Kerry &mdash; both Catholics who support legalized abortion and same-sex &ldquo;marriage&rdquo; &mdash; also praised the encyclical. During a White House-sponsored forum on clean energy, Biden <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.nationaljournal.com/energy/joe-biden-pope-francis-climate-change-encyclical-20150616">said </a>of Pope Francis, &ldquo;We have a good one now.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Kerry <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2015/06/243982.htm">called </a>the encyclical &ldquo;powerful&rdquo; and said the Pope&rsquo;s plea for all religions to work together &ldquo;reflects the urgency of the challenge.&rdquo;</p>

<p>Former Secretary of State Clinton, considered to be the leading Democratic presidential candidate, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/https://twitter.com/hillaryclinton/status/612002144686874627">tweeted </a>that Pope Francis is right about climate change, which she described as &ldquo;a moral crisis that disproportionately harms the neediest among us.&rdquo; Three hours earlier, Clinton also took to Twitter to <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/https://twitter.com/HillaryClinton/status/611970773260062720">praise </a>a pro-abortion decision by the Iowa Supreme Court.</p>

<p>Meanwhile, Martin O&rsquo;Malley, the former Maryland governor, who is also running for the Democratic presidential nomination, referenced Pope Francis&rsquo; encyclical at the start of a June 18 <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2015/06/18/pope-francis-encyclical-clean-energy-technology-campaign-column/28859409/">op-ed</a> he published in <em>USA Today </em>on renewable energy, incorrectly indicating that the papal document&rsquo;s primary focus was &ldquo;on the moral imperative of addressing climate change.&rdquo; O&rsquo;Malley, who is Catholic, supports abortion rights and signed a bill legalizing same-sex &ldquo;marriage&rdquo; in 2012.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p>Bernie Sanders, who has also announced his intention to run for the Democratic presidential nomination, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/https://twitter.com/sensanders/status/611517237866942464">tweeted </a>a picture of Pope Francis with a caption that the Pope&rsquo;s &ldquo;powerful message&rdquo; on climate change &ldquo;should change the debate around the world and become a catalyst for the bold actions needed to reverse global warming.&rdquo;</p>

<p>The political reactions to the encyclical show that ideology and partisanship &ldquo;are so powerful in America,&rdquo; said Stephen Schneck, director of the Institute for Policy Research &amp; Catholic Studies at The Catholic University of America.</p>

<p>&ldquo;They work like filters to screen out what people are able to comprehend. For those infected, inconvenient truths can be very hard to see,&rdquo; said Schneck, who co-chaired Catholics for Obama during the 2012 campaign.</p>

<p>Schneck told the Register he does not believe the cool response to <em>Laudato Si</em> by Republicans means that they are rejecting the Pope&rsquo;s moral authority.</p>

<p>&ldquo;And I don&rsquo;t think it&rsquo;s crass deference to polluting industries,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;I think the Pope is challenging all of us to think about creation in a new, moral way that does not fit into America&rsquo;s ideological filters.&rdquo;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Cardinals&rsquo; Perspectives</strong></p>

<p>Cardinal Peter Turkson<strong>, </strong>president of the Pontifical Council for Justice and Peace, <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-06-18/vatican-says-jeb-bush-should-listen-to-pope-on-climate-change">criticized</a> the statements of &ldquo;the Republicans and presidential figures who say they will not listen to the Pope&rdquo; during the June 18 Vatican press conference introducing <em>Laudato Si</em>. &ldquo;We talk about these subject matters not because we are experts on those matters; we talk about them because they concern the impact on our lives,&rdquo; said Cardinal Turkson, who specifically criticized Bush&rsquo;s remarks in a subsequent <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.cnn.com/videos/world/2015/06/18/intv-amanpour-cardinal-peter-turkson-jeb-bush.cnn">CNN interview</a>.</p>

<p>But in an <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://video.foxnews.com/v/4311350106001/cardinal-donald-wuerl-on-popes-climate-change-message/#sp=show-clips">interview </a>with <em>Fox News Sunday</em>, Cardinal Donald Wuerl, archbishop of Washington, sought to provide context to the political discussions over <em>Laudato Si</em>. He said Bush had a &ldquo;legitimate position&rdquo; in saying that he does not get his economic advice from the clergy.</p>

<p>Cardinal Wuerl said Pope Francis is not submitting a political agenda that politicians must accept.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Whether it&rsquo;s economics, whether it&rsquo;s politics, whether it&rsquo;s finance: Everything has a moral dimension to it because it&rsquo;s human,&rdquo; Cardinal Wuerl said. &ldquo;And what the Pope is holding up for us is: We can&rsquo;t just close in on ourselves, our own political interests, our economic or financial interests or political interests. We have to look at this through the moral dimension of: How does this affect everybody on the planet?&rdquo;</p>

<p style="text-align:right"><em><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20170227043512/http://www.ncregister.com/tags/9378">Brian Fraga</a> writes from Fall River, Massachusetts.</em></p></div>
    

        
        <div id="article-footer-ad" class="ad-slot article-footer">
  
</div>

        
          
