        <div class="comment-by">
          Posted by Mark C on Friday, Jun, 26, 2015 7:23 PM (EST):
        </div>
        <div class="comment-body">
          <p>It is noteworthy that Pres. Obama&#8217;s statement on Laudato Si does not acknowledge anything in the encyclical regarding abortion/population control.&nbsp; He got what he wanted: affirmation by the pope of his view that climate change is a crisis and human activity is a major contributor.&nbsp; This lends the president a certain moral authority to further push his environmentalist agenda.&nbsp; Expect the upcoming United Nations meeting to likewise ignore these sub-topics while its other agencies continue to push abortion as a human &#8220;right&#8221; and contraception as a silver bullet to address poverty in third-world as well as developed countries.</p>

<p>The pope could very well have stated in his encyclical how we all need to be good stewards of God&#8217;s creation, etc. without an explicit endorsement of the &#8220;consensus&#8221; that climate change is, a) a crisis, and, b) in large part due to human activity in recent decades.&nbsp; He could have said that while the controversial topic is still being studied and debated, we can and should all do our part to minimize pollution, etc.&nbsp; Could he not foresee that major world players will take the parts they want from the document (the &#8216;science&#8217; part) and throw out all the others that are inconvenient (the &#8216;religious&#8217; part)?&nbsp; If this is a crisis that has been going on for decades, were previous popes negligent in not sounding the alarm?</p>

<p>Jesus said (and I paraphrase here) that if the world hates you, it hated Me first.&nbsp; It is amazing to see how the &#8216;world&#8217; loves Pope Francis.&nbsp; Something to ponder&#8230;</p>



